      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Option is a contract which gives right and not an obligation to either buy or sell a particular underlying asset at a particular price before the contract end date. Since it’s just a contract to buy asset at a future date there is a premium associated with it and not the actual value of the asset. Usually the value of the contract is not more than 10% of the total value of the assets represented by the options contract. By trading in options one is managing a large amount of assets by paying relatively low options prices.</p>
<p>As the options contract represents the underlying asset the premium to be paid for the same is also based upon the fluctuations in the value of underlying asset. Below are some of the pricing related questions that may rise in the mind of traders:</p>
<p><strong>What is the difference between in-the-money and out-of-the-money?</strong><br />
In-the-money trade is the one which has an intrinsic value associated with it. So if the underlying assets current market price is way above the strike price in case of call option and if the current market price is way below the strike price in case of put option then the trade is in-the-money.<br />
Out-of-the-money is the opposite of in-the-money. So if the underlying asset’s market price is below the strike price in case of call options and if the market price is above the strike price in case of put options then the trade is out-of-the-money.</p>
<p><strong>However at times traders do ask what is the reason for options not moving as much as the underlying asset? </strong><br />
The answer is options would not move in the same pace as the underlying assets value unless they are in the money or unless they are very close to the expiration.</p>
<p><strong> Some traders may also ask that even if the stock value increases by 2% even then what is the reason for the downward trend in the value of call option?</strong><br />
The answer is there are several different factors that make the value of an option rise or fall, namely, contract end date, strike price, interest rate, stock price, and volatility. Usually, if the price of underlying asset goes up and all other factors remain constant then the value of call option would also rise. However if the value of call option is falling then there may be some other factors that are not performing in favor of the trade.</p>
