      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Stock <a title="Option trading" href="http://www.optiontradebasics.com/Getting-Started-With-Options">Option trading</a> is not for novice, however if you have worked hard enough to understand the fundamentals of stock options it can be a great money making and hedging instrument for your portfolio.</p>
<p><strong>So what is the difference between Stocks trading and Stock Option trading?</strong></p>
<p>One of the core differences is stocks offer a stake in the company or a small part of ownership of the company, where as stock option just provides a right to buy or sell stock of a company at a predefined price and within a certain time frame. Any trade can be carried out only if there is a buyer and a seller for a particular instrument; so as there are buyers for call and put options likewise there are also sellers for call and put options.</p>
<p><strong>Now you might be thinking how can a trader use Stock Option?</strong></p>
<p>A trader can use stock option in following ways:</p>
<ul>
<li>A trader can actually buy and sell the underlying asset      (stock) through buying and selling of call and put stock option.</li>
<li>Trader can buy and sell the contract for profit, and      not for exercising any rights associated with the contract.</li>
<li>One can also use options for hedging their current      portfolio against possible losses.</li>
</ul>
<p>Additionally, if a trader is holding the underlying stock then he/she can apply some very interesting and money making strategies if they add stock options to their portfolio.</p>
<p>For example: If you already own stocks of a particular company and you wish to book your profits then you can buy a put option at a strike price which is above the current market price but at a price which gives you better returns then prevailing market price. So if the market price falls then you can exercise your right and sell your stocks as per the contract and if the market price move upward you can forget about the premium paid for the contract and sell your stocks in the spot market.</p>
<p>Likewise some traders are only looking for a profit from the market fluctuations so they simply buy an option contract with no intention of exercising their rights and sell the contract for profit. These types of traders are also known as “speculators”.</p>
<p>The above information shows how important stock <a title="options trading" href="http://www.optiontradebasics.com/Getting-Started-With-Options">options trading</a> can be for the traders for making their portfolio more profitable and less risk averse.</p>
