      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>There is no trading venture where there would be no risks involved. The degree of risks may be different from trade to trade, and if there is more risks involved there are more chances of a trader getting excellent returns. Like any other trade <a title="Options trading" href="http://www.optiontradebasics.com/Getting-Started-With-Options">Options trading</a> also has a matter of risk in it.</p>
<p>First of all if someone asks what is the prime feature that makes <a title="option trading" href="http://www.optiontradebasics.com/Getting-Started-With-Options">option trading</a> risky? Then most option traders would agree with “Leverage” as the prime feature. Leverage does offer you advantage however it also has a power to snatch away your prospective gains if one fails to choose a right option at a right time. Leverage looks so lucrative which make people trade option but it is also damaging if not played in a right manner.</p>
<p>As per a finance professor’s wisdom, leverage means investing relatively less amount of money but still getting equal profits as if you have invested in full amount of the asset. This definitely sounds good but the problem is high leverage brings along a matter of higher risk.</p>
<p>Also there are different types of risks namely buyer’s risk and seller’s risk. Let’s look at what do they exactly mean one by one.</p>
<p><strong>1.) </strong><strong>Buyer’s Risk: </strong>In this type of trade there is a risk of losing your whole investment in a very short time horizon. Of course it sounds pretty interesting that one can as good as manage an asset for a time period with a fraction of its original investments by trading in option. However, if you have invested in an option contract which ends two months from now and if the value of stock stays below the strike price then the call option trader may have a chance of losing money. Additionally, the more near you are to the end of the contract and the price of the stock not in your favor, you tend to lose more and more money.<strong></strong></p>
<p><strong>2.) </strong><strong>Seller’s Risk:</strong> As buyer of the option contract has risk same is the case with the sellers of the option contract. So if trades are not made correctly or if the market mechanisms work against your trade then there is a possibility that seller will lose money.<strong></strong></p>
<p>Whatever may be the case, one should not only look at the risks involved but they should also consider the profit potential that option trading has.</p>
