      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Even though there are lots of Financial Terms in general that one might not be aware about, but for beginners following are some of the most used terms:</p>
<p><em>Option</em> – is a contract which gives the buyer a right to either buy or sell the underlying asset at a predefined strike price before the expiration of the contract. Further, buyer of the contract has a right and not an obligation to buy or sell the underlying asset.</p>
<p><em>Call Option</em> – Buyer of the Call option has a right to buy the underlying asset.</p>
<p><em>Put option</em> – Buyer of the Put option has a right to sell the underlying asset.</p>
<p><em>Exercise</em> – Buyer of the contract can practice his rights to buy (in case of call option) or to sell (in case of put option) the underlying asset or just ignore their rights and let the contract expire. If the buyer of the contract decides to exercise his rights he needs to intimate the seller regarding the same.</p>
<p><em>Expiration</em> – is the date when the contract is terminated. So if buyer of the contract wants to exercise his rights he needs to act upon the same before the end date of the contract.</p>
<p><em>In the money</em> – is when the underlying asset’s value is more than the strike price of call option. In case of Put option In the money is when the underlying assets value is less than the strike price.</p>
<p><em>Out of the money</em> – is when the underlying asset’s value is less than the strike price of call option. In case of Put option Out of the money is when the underlying assets value is more than the strike price.</p>
<p><em>Offsetting</em> – is when buyer of the contract exercises his rights, that is either buying or selling the stock during the contract period when he/she thinks that here is when he will get maximum benefits out of the trade.</p>
<p><em>Strike Price</em> – is the value at with the stock will be either bought or sold when the trader decides to offset his position. There are different Strike Prices available for the traders to trade in, ranging from Strike Price higher or lower than the stock’s current market value.</p>
<p><em>Option Premium</em> – Price paid for buying call or put option contract is called premium. Premium paid on the option are usually not more than 10% of the market value of the underlying stock.</p>
